lm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margarethe","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":8,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":53,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margareth De Scures was born in 1329, in Wickham, Hampshire, England. She married Sir John Wickham De Scures in 1350, in Wickham, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1329–":"1329–Surnud","1325–1353":"1325–1353","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1453":"1453","1353":"1353","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1329":"1329","Fareham, Hampshire, England":"Fareham, Hampshire, England","Wickham, Hampshire, England":"Wickham, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1329–":"1329–Kuollut","1325–1353":"1325–1353","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","